<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="311" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,295,320]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Both sexes of 
<taxonomicName box="[488,629,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gobiensis">
<emphasis box="[488,629,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">H. gobiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a short second segment of the labial palpus, which is only slightly longer than the first segment (
<figureCitation box="[486,570,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 11 – 14. 11" captionStartId="10.[151,249,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,573,1865]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,573,1866]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 11 – 14. 11: Hoplitis dispersipunctata, scutum and scutellum of female. 12: Hoplitis dispersipunctata, sterna 3 - 6 of male. 13: Hoplitis gobiensis, proboscis of female. 14: Hoplitis gobiensis, sterna 2 – 6 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229656/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
Fig. 
<number box="[539,570,332,356]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
). This character is shared only with 
<taxonomicName box="[975,1174,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassipunctata">
<emphasis box="[975,1174,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">H. crassipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1228,1346,333,356]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis box="[1228,1346,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">H. minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which, however, have different distribution areas. In addition, 
<taxonomicName box="[774,916,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gobiensis">
<emphasis box="[774,916,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">H. gobiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName box="[1067,1267,369,392]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassipunctata">
<emphasis box="[1067,1267,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">H. crassipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the smaller size, the finer punctation of the body, the less impressed apical zones of terga 
<number box="[1033,1076,404,428]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
and the lack of a distinct apical spine on the female fore coxa, and from 
<taxonomicName box="[616,736,441,464]" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Osmia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis box="[616,736,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">H. minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the pilosity of female tergum 
<number box="[1120,1136,439,464]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" value="5.0">5</number>
, which does not cover the whole tergal surface, and the presence of a longitudinal keel on male sternum 
<number box="[1024,1038,476,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" value="6.0">6</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[1053,1137,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 11 – 14. 11" captionStartId="10.[151,249,1899,1921]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,573,1865]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,573,1866]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 11 – 14. 11: Hoplitis dispersipunctata, scutum and scutellum of female. 12: Hoplitis dispersipunctata, sterna 3 - 6 of male. 13: Hoplitis gobiensis, proboscis of female. 14: Hoplitis gobiensis, sterna 2 – 6 of male." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/229656/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="311">
Fig. 
<number box="[1106,1137,476,500]" pageId="10" pageNumber="311" value="14.0">14</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
